Turkey expands its diplomatic horizons
Much before Turkey intended to be a member of the European Union, the European powers wanted to penetrate the country.
In the eastern part of the Bosphorus, just 20 steps into Asia, is one of the most interesting relics of the disastrous imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the guides say.
The building is placed on the end of the platforms and has two towers in front, one for each corner, resembling a typical German town.
The stone is dirty.
The building in its complex is a bit decadent.
But once the box office was overcome, there is no doubt what the greatness of the company was that this was the westernmost door.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Bagdad Corporation.
Germany, a “latecomer” in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railway that cured to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond in what today is Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during the First World War.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Due to the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell under
British domination and when the forces advanced in Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German ally out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was also bad for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917 a train of ammunition exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was a sabotage.
Since then, the station has gone down and remained on the margins of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centers, serves – at least symbolically – to highlight Turkey’s willingness to broaden its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a new policy of cooperation.
The Turkish governmentins excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To evaluate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I climbed to a bowl and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the AKP leaders, an expert in foreign policy, Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning – about ten and a half hours later – after a shaking journey, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital – a new city, thought to rule a new secular state, away from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigmatic change in the Turkish consensus.
That has raised some suspicion in the West and, especially, in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure – built ad hoc – in a developing suburb, surrounded by mid-built shopping centers and “power bakeries” where middle-class managers in business costume – men and women – meet early in the morning to get along/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any party in Europe.
Dress, tie, I’m sure he still has a Blackberry.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighborhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he says.
Turkey has been cut off in its relations with its interior.
Today you have to look at the East and the West at the same time.
This is not a case if it is not towards one or the other.
You have to do both things.
“But surely at some point,” I ask him, “could Turkey be forced to choose?”
“Turkey,” he replies, “does not want to crush this election.”
Next, he highlights a point that almost everyone I’ve spoken to so far has recited to me almost from memory: the relations Turkey has not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the entire Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States States as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically mount those railway lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Again at the Hydarpasha station, after a second night without sleep, my thought returns to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building, 100 years ago.
How surprised would they have been to know that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East would largely be in Turkey’s hands today?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered “the sick man of Europe.”
Therefore, there is no doubt in what continent this fascinating country should claim.
