The Bee Car That Avoids Collisions
To advance in the development of accidents prevention technologies, Nissan has inspired, this time, nature, in particular, bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking as its basis the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Advanced Technical Center at Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious Tokyo University in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Chief Public Relations Officer for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand’s vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal space with an oval shape that resembles Nissan’s Safety Shield.
But the most important are the composite eyes of the bee, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterruptedly within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers designed what they have called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles at a distance of up to two meters within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately translates into collision prevention.
“As soon as it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a straight or larger angle to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to spin its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, as well as acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn’t require storing information or intuitive logic of previous operations, so it can work continuously with just a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we’re not talking about memory gigs, not even megas.”
This is the first step to developing new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology Nissan predicts will be introduced in production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ion batteries.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a satellite navigation GPS system to guide the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles on the road.
