Morgan Stanley shares lost 6.79 percent to $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance constitutes an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said Juan Mack, CEO of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have allowed him to diversify his activities but he makes it pass under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces the bigger names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious behavior than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: Monday, Morgan had announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG's chief executive, explained in Tokyo, "we thought the participation would have been made up only of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we have wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley bonds 7% below its accounting value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares within one year if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at $47 more or less, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that MUFG’s capital will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group declined, however, to give details on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should show a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan needed to have eased his balance sheet considerably since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been exhausting for the group, which saw its stock exchange quotation drop by half while the cost of security against a risk of defects on its debt took off.
This cost fell last Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the other only “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part for Berkshire Hathaway, the Warren Buffett group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refunding the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, at the example of his colleagues and friends, it is the third time that a draft for a new Constitution was put to the vote.
Mission fulfilled as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of the suffrages.
According to these results, the "no" received 28%, 7% of the suffrages were null votes and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half the suffrage plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and a count of a part of a non-governmental organization had announced a widespread victory for the "yes", estimating it between 63 percent and 70 percent.
Rafael Correa also claimed on Sunday night the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed crushingly,” he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who head the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
So, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will be held in full calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the “new socialism” defended by the president.
The draft Constitution implies the increase of the power of the State over the economy, reserving it the “development planning” of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to currencies that send its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants reinforced powers to the head of state, who will be able to do up to two consecutive four-year terms each and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and would seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of the gratuity of health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty threshold.
It finally prevents the ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. drug operations.
19 kidnapped people released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were abducted in the desert 10 days ago arrived safely in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good at their arrival at 15:30 a.m. on board a special aircraft to the Al Maza military base adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to undergo medical tests, so they could not speak to the press.
“They are in good health” and “no ransom was paid” to the hijackers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into power by 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying an all-terrain safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then passed from one Zulo to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of organizing the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
“An exchange of shots occurred, and they killed half of the hijackers, the others fled,” said this official who kept the anonymity.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the lightning unit were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men of the secret services, of the special forces," he said without entering into details.
He also denied the payment of a bailout.
On the eve, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrain on board of which were the hijackers, of whom it killed six, including the Chadian leader and detained two.
He also claimed that they were related to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a claim immediately dismissed by this group.
Literature: The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes the headlines and occupies the current election campaign.
Better that way.
But a sector of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites dying of hunger?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don’t we have true laws that effectively preserve our heritage like in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government is spending three and a half million euros to restore only the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of the Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and all this, in concertation.
In Quebec, in the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 benevolent people grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned about searching in history, preserving with little money lots of private archives and preserving archaeological vestiges.
These are often the guardian dogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and despair when promoters and leaders throw their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The government of the Netherlands nationalizes part of the Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands – being the first in Europe – will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the U.S. market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros this financial and insurance institution that also has in Hungary.
This weekend, the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s competition minister.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the eurozone crisis in the framework of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves more than a year ago, so decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense, can be considered as precedent.
According to the decision adopted on Sunday morning, the three states will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the bank’s ownership in their area.
The Bank will surely sell a portion of its business, including the activities – mainly insurance – purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis stocks started a sharp drop last week and for the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, this bank is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company’s shares dropped 12 percent on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Looking at the current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank's management blamed the sharp fall in Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the US market in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package.
On Monday, the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday they appointed Filip Dierckx as the bank’s new CEO.
The bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors had no need to worry, they would not lose their money.
Among the bank’s customers so far there has been no panic, they have not invaded the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Zorro in the Chicken
In the United States, life and health insurance companies, when looking at medication purchase details, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy experts fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of data from prescriptions in all cases binds it to the approval of the given person.
The same should be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we trust the chicken to the fox" - cites the Washington Post to Richard Dick, the designer of the medical prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the price of the insurance and the amount of compensation dependent on the customer’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply don’t make the contract.
Previously, they sent the client to medical check and signed the contract with him already knowing the outcome of the check.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer’s identification number he easily obtains from the pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the patient’s illnesses and health status.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-reducing pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even set a number of risks, so that the insurance company in addition to the administration barely has something to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multi-use, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk increasing factor for insurance companies while the first is not.
Special companies were established to consult and process these data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities have already forced them to do so, although they have not been fined for negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also developed the results of laboratory tests and by combining them with drug consumption data obtain more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it only applies to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill gives the authority the right to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data.
Dick Richard recognizes that this is insufficient: therefore he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, despite all, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
EU doubles trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutual trade partners, this issue in addition to other largely global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, primarily to address cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit started yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, turning president of the EU, José Manuel Barroso, president of the Commission, and Javier Solana, chief foreign policy representative, welcomed Manmohan Singh, prime minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase to more than 100 billion euros, their trade.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious goal.
Thus they legally harmonized the twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so that air transport can also fly in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to accelerate the negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi only ranks ninth among the EU’s trading partners.
The summit focused on global issues.
Both sides condemned the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism – all its forms – and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also crushed, although both sides have great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate program, meaning that by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20 percent.
India is also in agreement with this, just as next year’s climate conference should reach a global agreement and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to hinder the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today, the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency information, the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
