Steve Fossett's plane found missing a year ago
The remains of the plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The debris has been found on a plateau at 3,000 meters altitude, in the Nevada Sierra of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Wood County Commissioner John Anderson said: "The plane has been localized, we have sent a squadron, and now we have confirmation that it's own of what Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance."
The officer said no human remains were found in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old millionaire was found dead in February.
The American Office for Transportation Safety (NTSB) has that a few hours after the detection of the remains, a squadron of investigators has been sent to identify the apparatus: it is owned by the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the border of Nevada, some personal remains of Fossett have been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fossett, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had conquered a place in history thanks to a long series of primaries.
In 2002, at the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the world round in an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he had made the world round in a plane and without escalations.
Among his records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a copywriter.
